=========================================================
FRIEND FUNCTIONS IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
A Friend Function is a function that is NOT a member of a class but is
allowed to access the private and protected members of that class.

It is declared inside the class using the keyword:

friend

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED FRIEND FUNCTIONS?
=========================================================

Normally:

Private Members
      ↓
Accessible only inside class members.

Sometimes, an external function needs access to private data.

Examples:
• Operator Overloading
• Utility Functions
• Functions operating on multiple classes

Friend functions provide controlled access.

=========================================================
SYNTAX
=========================================================

class Test
{
private:
    int x;

public:
    friend void display(Test&);
};

void display(Test& t)
{
    cout << t.x;
}

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 1 : BASIC FRIEND FUNCTION
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Test
{
private:
    int x = 100;

public:
    friend void display(Test&);
};

void display(Test& t)
{
    cout << t.x;
}

int main()
{
    Test t;
    display(t);
}

Output:
100

Reason:
display() is not a member of Test, but can access private members
because it is declared as friend.

=========================================================
HOW DOES FRIEND FUNCTION WORK?
=========================================================

class Test
{
private:
    int x;

    friend void display(Test&);
};

Compiler grants access permission to:

display(Test&)

Even though it is not a class member.

=========================================================
IMPORTANT POINT
=========================================================

Friend function is:

✓ Not a member function
✓ Cannot use this pointer
✓ Called like normal functions
✓ Can access private and protected members

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Test
{
private:
    int x = 10;

public:
    friend void show(Test&);
};

void show(Test& t)
{
    cout << t.x;
}

int main()
{
    Test t;

    show(t);
}

Call:

show(t);

NOT:

t.show();

=========================================================
WHY CAN'T FRIEND FUNCTION USE this POINTER?
=========================================================

Because it is NOT a member of the class.

Only member functions receive:

this

pointer.

=========================================================
FRIEND FUNCTION ACCESSING MULTIPLE OBJECTS
=========================================================

class Test
{
private:
    int x;

public:
    Test(int a)
    {
        x = a;
    }

    friend void compare(Test&, Test&);
};

void compare(Test& t1, Test& t2)
{
    if (t1.x > t2.x)
        cout << "t1 greater";
    else
        cout << "t2 greater";
}

Friend functions can access private data of multiple objects.

=========================================================
WHY FRIEND FUNCTIONS ARE USEFUL?
=========================================================

Member function:

obj1.compare(obj2);

Friend function:

compare(obj1, obj2);

Symmetric operations are easier.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE : OPERATOR OVERLOADING
=========================================================

class Complex
{
private:
    int real;
    int imag;

public:
    Complex(int r, int i)
    {
        real = r;
        imag = i;
    }

    friend Complex operator+(Complex, Complex);
};

Complex operator+(Complex c1, Complex c2)
{
    return Complex(
            c1.real + c2.real,
            c1.imag + c2.imag
          );
}

int main()
{
    Complex c1(10,20);
    Complex c2(30,40);

    Complex c3 = c1 + c2;
}

One of the most common uses of friend functions.

=========================================================
FRIEND FUNCTION WITH TWO CLASSES
=========================================================

class B;

class A
{
private:
    int x = 100;

public:
    friend void display(A&, B&);
};

class B
{
private:
    int y = 200;

public:
    friend void display(A&, B&);
};

void display(A& a, B& b)
{
    cout << a.x << " "
         << b.y;
}

Output:
100 200

Friend function can access private members of multiple classes.

=========================================================
FRIEND CLASS
=========================================================

class A
{
private:
    int x = 10;

    friend class B;
};

class B
{
public:
    void display(A& a)
    {
        cout << a.x;
    }
};

Output:
10

Entire class B becomes friend of A.

=========================================================
FRIEND FUNCTION CHARACTERISTICS
=========================================================

1. Not a member of class.
2. Declared using friend keyword.
3. Called like normal functions.
4. No this pointer.
5. Can access private and protected members.
6. Can be declared anywhere in class.

=========================================================
CAN FRIEND FUNCTION BE DECLARED IN PRIVATE SECTION?
=========================================================

YES.

class Test
{
private:
    friend void display(Test&);
};

OR

class Test
{
public:
    friend void display(Test&);
};

Both are same.

Reason:
friend is not affected by access specifiers.

=========================================================
IS FRIENDSHIP INHERITED?
=========================================================

NO.

=========================================================

class A
{
    friend class B;
};

class C : public B
{
};

C is NOT friend of A.

=========================================================

Friendship is NOT inherited.

=========================================================
IS FRIENDSHIP TRANSITIVE?
=========================================================

NO.

A → B (friend)
B → C (friend)

Does NOT imply:

A → C

=========================================================
IS FRIENDSHIP MUTUAL?
=========================================================

NO.

class A
{
    friend class B;
};

B can access A.

A cannot access B automatically.

=========================================================
ADVANTAGES OF FRIEND FUNCTIONS
=========================================================

1. Allows controlled access to private data.
2. Useful in operator overloading.
3. Useful when working with multiple classes.
4. Reduces need for numerous getters/setters.
5. Enables symmetric operations.

=========================================================
DISADVANTAGES OF FRIEND FUNCTIONS
=========================================================

1. Breaks Encapsulation.
2. Increases Coupling.
3. Reduces Data Hiding.
4. Makes maintenance difficult if overused.

=========================================================
WHEN TO USE FRIEND FUNCTIONS?
=========================================================

✓ Operator Overloading
✓ Utility Functions
✓ Functions requiring access to multiple objects/classes
✓ Serialization/Debug helpers (occasionally)

Avoid using friend unnecessarily.

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is a Friend Function?

Answer:
A function that is not a member of a class but can access its private
and protected members.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Is friend function a member function?

NO.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Can friend function use this pointer?

NO.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Why is friend function needed?

Answer:
To provide controlled access to private data and for operator
overloading and multi-class operations.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Is friendship inherited?

NO.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Is friendship transitive?

NO.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Is friendship mutual?

NO.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. Can friend function be virtual?

NO.

Reason:
Friend functions are not member functions.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q9. Can friend function be static?

Global friend functions cannot be static members because they are not
class members.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER
=========================================================

A Friend Function is a non-member function that is granted access to a
class's private and protected members using the friend keyword. It is
commonly used in operator overloading and when a function needs access
to private data of multiple classes. Since it breaks encapsulation and
increases coupling, it should be used sparingly.

